{
  "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
  "$id": "https://aureline.dev/schemas/companion/ship-companion-safe-redaction-local-core-continuity-and-offline-packet-flows-across-support-and-incident-lanes.schema.json",
  "title": "Aureline companion-safe redaction, local-core continuity, and offline packet flows across support and incident lanes",
  "description": "Export-safe packet that ties the companion, incident, and support lanes together around three guarantees: every record that crosses a companion, support, or incident boundary is redaction-safe (no raw payload body crosses, and a redaction is proved where claimed or labeled where not); the local core stays authoritative and its capabilities keep working offline; and the support and incident packets that flow out assemble and replay offline from the local core. It projects four sections — redaction_policy, local_core_continuity, offline_incident_packet, and offline_support_packet. The redaction-policy section inherits qualification from the frozen M5 companion-matrix companion_notification lane, the incident-packet section from the incident_workspace lane, and the continuity and support-packet sections from the offboarding_continuity lane; every item carries an exact desktop handoff. Read-only projection with the local core authoritative: every section is read-only, the surface only projects state (redaction is enforced and a packet is assembled by the local core, never authored from this surface), and a local-first incident-packet and support-packet path is always offered as a fallback. Companion-safe redaction: no raw payload body crosses any boundary, and a redaction claim is shown as proven only when verifiable (an unverifiable claim narrows the redaction to a more conservative class and is labeled). Offline packet flows: a completeness claim is proved where claimed or labeled where not, and an incident packet stays attributable or is honestly labeled. Local-core continuity never strands user-owned local work. Degraded state (redaction proof unavailable, packet assembler unavailable, stale proof, completeness unverified, incident attribution unavailable, managed service degraded, inactive host, narrowed upstream lane, unresolved handoff, downgraded freshness, redaction narrowed to reference, packet narrowed to local path, downgraded completeness claim, narrowed attribution) is labeled rather than hidden. Credential bodies, raw provider payloads, raw incident evidence bodies, and raw support-bundle contents never cross this boundary.",
